issue.title: Full spec is AI generated
issue.body:
With the overwhelming amount of AI slop that has been included in issues, PRs, and other Raven Dev Team repos, I decided to put the spec's markdown in an AI checker. The results say 100% of it was AI generated and that makes sense with all the issues and inconsistencies the spec contains. I've shared a link below to the AI checker that I've used.

https://app.gptzero.me/documents/08974092-6a67-4555-a133-9883eee2e9aa/share

Personally, I'd like to think that this is a just a kid with good intentions striving to make a better internet, but LLMs are not the way to go about it. LLMs are just summarizing tools. They are not good at creating new ideas. They just summarize knowledge it already has already been trained by.

But then, things got real when he received a $50k donation to get this going, and now, he's just trying to handle it the best he can. Realistically, $50k is nowhere near enough manpower to bootstrap a new Internet layer, but, even so, there is entire community being built around Betanet. I've met some cool people and I'm sure you have too, but will this project turn into something real? Probably not. 

The only really decent, concrete idea that has come from this is using a mock TLS connection to mask other protocols. Why not put that over Tor or I2p? I don't know. Everything else, the protocol upgradability, the financial incentives for routing, are not new. Many blockchains have an upgrade protocol more sophisticated than just release the update and hope people start running the new version. Financial incentives have been available for years using Althea (althea.net).

comment.body:
> > But what I would know, is that people, are advocating for this project, a privacy-focused, censorship free idea of a new layer of internet protocols is something that a LOT of people need in this time and age of digital footprints.
> 
> Just use something like Tor or I2P, they are already fully developed and have a large community. This project is essentially trying to do the same thing, so why try to reinvent the wheel? By the way, I hope you're doing good in Iraq .

Thank you for the kind words, I hope you're doing good as well! <3

You are correct, we can use Tor or I2P, it is indeed as good as Betanet, and might've be even better. But the thing is, the ISPs in Iraq monitor the users HEAVILY, they will know for sure if you're connected to a Tor or I2P node, the infrastructure of communication layers here in Iraq are implemented in such a way that the Iraqi national security (in other words the Iraqi version of the NSA & FBI but corrupt) will literally know your location because the ISPs here are always in a monitor-and-report mode. Now I am not saying that our censorship is at the extreme level such as Iran or North Korea, but it is at a, let's say, medium-level of censorship in which you cannot criticize a public official if they're corrupt, or else their corrupt police would be knocking your door. 

Iraqi ministry of communications blocked the app Telegram entirely for a month because there was a leak regarding official corrupt documents, as well as citizen data.

Which is the reason of why I fully endorsed this type of project in the first place, it is a long shot in the dark, a massive project, if it hits, it would be beneficial for everyone. Just a basic freedom that people here need right now :)

build-push.ymlstep
"""
name: Build and Push 

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - "main"
  workflow_dispatch:

env:
  ALIYUN_REGISTRY: ${{ vars.ALIYUN_REGISTRY }}
  ALIYUN_REGISTRY_USER: ${{ secrets.ALIYUN_REGISTRY_USER }}
  ALIYUN_REGISTRY_PWD: ${{ secrets.ALIYUN_REGISTRY_PWD }}
  API_IMAGE_NAME: ${{ vars.API_IMAGE_NAME }}

jobs:
  changes:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    outputs:
      api: ${{ steps.filter.outputs.api }}
      workflow: ${{ steps.filter.outputs.workflow }}
    steps:
      - name: Checkout
        uses: actions/checkout@v3
      
      - name: Check for file changes
        uses: dorny/paths-filter@v2
        id: filter
        with:
          base: ${{ github.event.before }}
          filters: |
            api:
              - 'api/**'
            web:
              - 'web/**'
            workflow:
              - '.github/workflows/**'


api-build-and-push:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: [changes]
        if:  needs.changes.outputs.api == 'true' || needs.changes.outputs.workflow == 'true' || github.event_name == 'workflow_dispatch'
    steps:
      - name: Checkout
        uses: actions/checkout@v3

      - name: Set up Docker Buildx
        uses: docker/setup-buildx-action@v2

      - name: Login to Aliyun Container Registry
        uses: docker/login-action@v2
        with:
          registry: ${{ env.ALIYUN_REGISTRY }}
          username: ${{ env.ALIYUN_REGISTRY_USER }}
          password: ${{ env.ALIYUN_REGISTRY_PWD }}

      - name: Extract metadata (tags, labels) for Docker
        id: meta
        uses: docker/metadata-action@v4
        with:
          images: |
            ${{ env.ALIYUN_REGISTRY }}/${{ env.API_IMAGE_NAME }}

      - name: Build and push Api Docker image
        uses: docker/build-push-action@v4
        with:
          context: api
          push: true
          file: api/Dockerfile
          tags: ${{ steps.meta.outputs.tags }}
          labels: ${{ steps.meta.outputs.labels }}
"""

pull_request.body:
This PR implements a new GitHub Actions workflow `build-push.yml` that builds and pushes Docker images to Aliyun Container Registry when changes are pushed to the main branch.

## Key Features

- **Automatic triggering**: Activates on pushes to `main` branch and supports manual dispatch
- **Conditional building**: Uses file change detection to only build when `api/**` or workflow files are modified
- **Latest stable actions**: Updates all GitHub Actions to their newest stable versions for improved security and performance
- **Registry integration**: Seamlessly integrates with Aliyun Container Registry using environment variables and secrets

## Technical Implementation

The workflow consists of two main jobs:

1. **Change Detection**: Uses `dorny/paths-filter@v3` to detect relevant file changes
2. **Build and Push**: Conditionally builds and pushes the API Docker image using the latest Docker actions

## Action Version Updates

All GitHub Actions have been updated to their latest stable versions:
- `actions/checkout@v3`  `@v4`
- `docker/setup-buildx-action@v2`  `@v3` 
- `docker/login-action@v2`  `@v3`
- `docker/metadata-action@v4`  `@v5`
- `docker/build-push-action@v4`  `@v6`
- `dorny/paths-filter@v2`  `@v3`

## Environment Configuration

The workflow requires the following environment variables to be configured in the repository:

**Repository Variables:**
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY` - Aliyun container registry URL
- `API_IMAGE_NAME` - Target image name

**Repository Secrets:**
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY_USER` - Registry username
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY_PWD` - Registry password

## Workflow Relationship

This new workflow complements the existing `only-build.yml` workflow:
- `only-build.yml`: Builds (but doesn't push) on non-main branches
- `build-push.yml`: Builds and pushes on main branch

This ensures a complete CI/CD pipeline where feature branches are validated through build-only testing, while the main branch automatically deploys to the container registry.
